accessibility.text: First-order motion
MT
pasted-image.jpg
First order signals are pooled over a larger area in area MT
Pooling loses information about position
V1

Presenter notes Each cell in V1 detects motion in a very small region of visual space, but it turns out we cannot consciously access those signals. The signals that reach perception flow from V1 though other areas like MT.
(build) Basically the signals of many cells in V1 which are consistent with a particular direction of motion are combined to produce a signal in MT for that direction.

(build) This pooling of information loses information about position. So, if you were to have a simple motion signal like this, it would be seen at rightward motion, but a stimulus like this — think of a dot the travels a bit right, then jumps further left — locally matches the rightward templates of each V1 cell, but the fact that the actual locus of this stimulus is traveling right to left, is lost when all these signals are pooled in MT.
As it turns out, no convincing correlates of “position defined motion” have been found in area MT.
